feedback-fq1:
For shortest path questions, I hovered over both of the target nodes and tried to eyeball which adjacent nodes were most likely to be on the shortest path. This worked pretty well when the path was short but was less reliable for longer ones.

For counting the number of neighbors with a given degree, I hovered over the target node then swept my eyes in a circle around each neighbor. If it was ambiguous (e.g. because of overlapping edges) I would double check by hovering on the neighbor.
feedback-fq2: There were two main challenges. On every visualization style, edges sometimes overlapped visually which made it necessary to rely on the hover tool to figure out what was going on. And specifically on the last style, the fisheye effect made it difficult to have both highlighted nodes clearly in view, which made finding a shortest path more difficult.
feedback-fq4: The last style was visually fun, but less intuitive than the globe and the plane. I guess the main advantage would be automatically magnifying the focused node, but I feel like the effect was too strong here, making it hard to look at the whole graph all at once.

feedback-fq1: Most of the questions I was able to double click or drag to find the highlighted vertices, then hover over vertices to see their connections.  To count how many neighbors had degree d I just hovered over each neighbor.  Finding shortest paths by eye is harder, so mostly I found a reasonably short path that didn't obviously look like there were any shortcuts.
feedback-fq4: I love the aesthetics of the hyperbolic graph embeddings.  The most difficult thing about using that one was that finding paths between two vertices was somewhat complicated by not being able to have both vertices nicely on-screen at the same time.  But at least once I think I noticed a shorter path that I would have overlooked if not for the extra "local space" the visualization provided.

feedback-fq1: I rely heavily on the hovering tool where the nodes and the edges are highlighted when I hover my mouse over the nodes. I use this to find linked nodes when the a small region has a lot of nodes together. I also use it to find the neighbors of the highlighted node and move my cursor back and forth between the target node and its neighbors to count edges. I also use the double-click feature often center the target node so I can easily check neighbors and edges.
feedback-fq2: Using the trackpad on a mac laptop makes zooming in and out very difficult because the sensitivity was too high. You might find your data that my zooming in and out is too extreme. This is why I did not find this feature helpful for answering questions.
feedback-fq4: The globe visualization is very confusing to use. Sometimes, click-and-drag between left side and right side moves the graph between left and right. Other times, click-and-drag between left side and right side rotates the graph clockwise and counterclockwise. It was not until answering about half the questions using this globe visualization that I realize that there are north and south poles where the graph move left and right when my view is centered at the equator and rotate clockwise and counterclockwise when my view is centered at the poles. I like the globe warping visualization the most. It sort-of zoomed in as a look for a path between target nodes, and it allowed me to discover shorter paths I wouldn't have otherwise found with other visualizations. This view also allows me to focus on the current graph information while getting the gist of other sections of the graph so I do not have to click-and-drag to get the information I need. I do NOT like the normal globe visualization.
